{
  "text": "Effective treatments for cognitive symptoms remain an unmet need in schizophrenia. While advances have been made towards understanding the underlying neurobiology, further insight is essential for translational success [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . Following strong and replicated genetic association findings of BRD1 with schizophrenia [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] Pardi\u00f1as et al., 2016; [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] , behavioral alterations with translational relevance to schizophrenia, including impaired performance in a number of cognitive tasks, have been documented in Brd1 +/\u00c0 mice (Qvist et al., 2016) . The present study elaborates the cognitive characterization of Brd1 +/\u00c0 mice by employing additional rodent tasks with translational value to the cognitive domains affected in schizophrenia. These results further highlight the Brd1 +/\u00c0 mouse model as a valuable tool for studying the neurobiology of schizophrenia. We summarize the cognitive deficits of Brd1 +/\u00c0 mice in Table 2 . Although none of the cognitive deficits are pathognomonic of schizophrenia, the MATRICS and CNTRICS initiatives have specifically highlighted working memory, speed of processing, attention and vigilance, verbal learning and memory, visual learning and memory, reasoning and problem solving, perception, long term memory and social cognition as affected domains in schizophrenia [CITATION_9] [CITATION_10] . Except verbal learning and memory, the other cognitive domains can be tested in rodent models with varying levels of difficulty [CITATION_11] . We have already reported long-term social and declarative memory deficits in Brd1 +/\u00c0 mice. Additionally, Brd1 +/\u00c0 mice displayed reduced capacity in the glutamatergic transmission to support perception and working memory as measured by PPI and spontaneous-and continuous alternation tasks in Y maze when challenged by PCP (Qvist et al., 2016) .",
